Here's the registration:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // One HttpClient + data service instance for the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // New ViewModel per navigation so each screen gets fresh state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // New page per navigation (MAUI doesn't reuse pages well)
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | Singleton | Reuse connections, avoid socket exhaustion |
| `IDataService` | Singleton | Holds the shared `HttpClient`; acts as a stateless gateway to the API — one instance is enough |
| ViewModels | Transient | Each navigation should get a fresh VM with clean state (no stale data from a previous visit) |
| Pages | Transient | MAUI pages carry UI state; transient avoids rendering artifacts when navigating back to the same page type |

**Key rule of thumb:** if it's stateless infrastructure → **singleton**; if it carries per-screen state → **transient**. Avoid `AddScoped` in MAUI — there's no meaningful scope like an HTTP request in ASP.NET Core.

> **Note:** For production, consider replacing the raw `AddSingleton<HttpClient>()` with `builder.Services.AddHttpClient<IDataService, DataService>()` from `Microsoft.Extensions.Http` — it manages handler rotation and avoids DNS caching issues.
